article.headline: Minnesota 77, South Dakota State 53
article.story: MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Spencer Tollackson had a smile on his face Thursday night that has not been seen often this season. That's what happens when a team whose confidence has been shaken gets boosted by easily defeating a foe that it should. Dan Coleman continued his strong play by scoring a career-high 28 points, and Lawrence McKenzie added 15, to lead Minnesota past South Dakota State 77-53 Thursday. "Winning solves a lot of problems," said Tollackson, who added nine points and six rebounds for Minnesota (4-6), which won for just the second time in eight games. It was the second win in three games for interim coach Jim Molinari, who took over when Dan Monson resigned one week earlier. To win by such a wide margin is even better, especially during a stretch of four games in eight days, and coming after a double-overtime loss Tuesday at Alabama-Birmingham. "I felt like in a few games in the past we'd get up and then get back down, or they'd be a lot closer, so it was nice just to finally get one of those confidence games and get some other guys some experience," Tollackson said. "I'm just happy that we played well and some of the guys that play more significant minutes could get some more rest tonight." Minnesota's starters were pulled from the game midway through the second half. Ten players scored for the Gophers, and the two that didn't score, Kevin Payton and Jonathan Williams, played 12 and 14 minutes respectively. Michael Loney led South Dakota State (2-8) with 13 points, two more than Kai Williams. Matt Cadwell, who earned all-state honors at Cretin-Derham Hall High School in St. Paul, had eight points, ending his streak of five straight games as the team's high scorer. Coleman, averaging 18.4 points in last five contests, has scored in double figures in eight of his 10 games. "Him hitting jump shots, him coming off the pick-and-pops and going to the basket and scoring and rebounding is definitely something he can do all year if he puts his mind to it," McKenzie said. "I'm looking forward to seeing him doing that." Coleman, whose previous high was 23 points, had 20 points in the opening half and keyed a Minnesota run that opened up a close game. But he knows this is not a one-man game. "I was just trying to get to the basket, but my teammates were giving me some nice assists," Coleman said. "Most of our buckets were coming off assists so everyone was moving the ball and trying to get each other involved." Minnesota had a season-high 24 assists, and shot 56.1 percent from the field, also a season best. The Gophers had just 10 turnovers, after averaging 18.4 miscues in its past five games. South Dakota State, which started three guards, used strong outside shooting to open a 23-17 lead midway through the opening half. "It'd be amazing to think this way, but I think our players got overconfident like they just thought (Minnesota) would roll over," said Jackrabbits coach Scott Nagy. Instead, the Gophers went on a 28-5 run in the final 10 minutes, capped by layups from Coleman and McKenzie for a 45-28 lead. Coleman scored 11 points during the run; McKenzie 10. "Coach Mo said he's going to keep believing in us," McKenzie said. "We had a rough start, a slow start, but we knew we were prepared to pull it out if we kept going and kept grinding it out." A 3-pointer by Cadwell got South Dakota State again within 17 points early in the second half, but the Jackrabbits would get got no closer, falling behind by as many as 33 points.
